model.hed: *Dreamgirls*, *Nine,* and the Greatest Face-Off in Tony Award History
model.dek: Michael Bennett’s *Dreamgirls,* backed by the powerful Shubert theater empire, was up against up-and-coming director Tommy Tune’s *Nine,* thrown together on a shoestring.

items.title: Stephanie Cotsirilos and Liliane Montevecchi go glam.
Holliday and Bennett at the show’s opening-night after-party, December 1981.
Anita Morris, as Carla, shows off William Ivey Long’s black lace catsuit.
Jennifer Holliday, Sheryl Lee Ralph, and Loretta Devine in *Dreamgirls,* 1981.
A high-spirited Tune in front of a poster for Bennett’s *A Chorus Line,* 1980.
Al Hirschfeld’s illustration of Julia and the all-female ensemble, 1982.
Producers David Geffen and Bernie Jacobs collaborate with director Bennett.
Deborah Burrell, Ralph, and Devine wear white Dreamettes gowns, 1981.
items.credit: By Martha Swope/© The New York Public Library.

items.title: Michael Bennett (right) helps Tommy Tune stage a number at a rehearsal for the 1980 Tony Awards telecast.
*Nine’*s director, Tommy Tune, flanked by dancer Ann Miller and comedian Milton Berle, triumphantly shows off his 1982 Tony.
Raul Julia with the Pink Ladies in *Nine,* 1982.

fields.name: Vanity Fair
fields.bio: *Vanity Fair* features in-depth reporting, gripping narratives, and world-class photography, plus heaping doses of Oscar-blogging, royal-watching, and assorted guilty pleasures.  Every month,the magazine commissions the best writers and photographers to explain the pressing issues of the day and take the pulse of the culture. Vanity Fair consistently delivers crucial reporting on business and finance, domestic politics and world affairs, even as it covers the very best in arts and entertainment.
